The paper deals with the state complexity of regular languages, which is a fundamental concept in formal language theory. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory). The paper also involves the use of derivatives of regular expressions, which is a technique commonly used in data structures (cs.DS). The problem of finding the quotient complexity of regular operations involves combinatorial counting, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.CC) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The paper also presents new general observations to help in the estimation of upper bounds, which could fall under the category of logic in computer science (cs.LO) or information theory (cs.IT).
